The goal of our work is to consider only those excited electronic states, which are localized on the semiconductor particle, i.e. BODIPY and GQD (Fig. 2
                     ). All excited electrons, which were found to be localized on the water molecule, were disregarded from subsequent consideration. The first excited states of BODIPY and GQD, as exemplified in Table 1, can be obtained by transferring an electron from HOMO-N, where N
                     =1–4, to LUMO or LUMO+1.

The case of BODIPY and water interaction, which is primarily electrostatic, is compared to the case of GQD and water (Fig. 5
                     ), which is of the van der Waals nature. Indeed, graphene and GQDs are known for their hydrophobicity and insolubility in polar solvents, such as water. In the ground state, the attraction per electron is an order of magnitude smaller, as compared to the case of BODIPY. The attraction increases twofold (ca. 100%, Fig. 6
                     ) in the third and fourth excited states. Unlike the above case of BODIPY, higher separations of GQD and water do not lead to larger relative differences in the binding energies between the states.
